**God Object (SRP)**
```csharp
public class OrderProcessor {
    public void ProcessOrder() {}
    public void SendConfirmationEmail() {}
    public void UpdateInventory() {}
    //... and so on for other business operations
}
```
This code smells of God Object because it has too many responsibilities. It is responsible for processing an order, sending a confirmation email, updating inventory, etc., all in one class. This violates the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) as per SOLID principles. 

Refactoring:
```csharp
public interface IOrderProcessor {
    void ProcessOrder();
}

public interface IEmailSender {
    void SendConfirmationEmail();
}

public interface IInventoryUpdater {
    void UpdateInventory();
}

// Implement each interface in separate classes.
```
**Interface Bloat (ISP)**
The above refactored code violates the Interface Segregation Principle (ISP). The `IOrderProcessor`, `IEmailSender` and `IInventoryUpdater` interfaces are bloated with methods that they don't need. 

Refactoring:
```csharp
public interface IOrderProcessor {
    void ProcessOrder();
}

public interface IOrderConfirmation {
    void SendConfirmationEmail();
}

public interface IInventoryUpdater {
    void UpdateInventory();
}
// Implement each interface in separate classes.
```
**Inappropriate Intimacy (DIP)**
The above refactored code violates the Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP). The high-level modules should not depend on low-level modules, both should depend on abstractions. 

Refactoring:
```csharp
public interface IOrderProcessor {
    void ProcessOrder();
}

public interface IOrderConfirmation {
    void SendConfirmationEmail();
}

public interface IInventoryUpdater {
    void UpdateInventory();
}
// Implement each interface in separate classes. Then, pass instances of these classes to the classes that need them. 
```
**LSP Violation (ISP)**
The above refactored code does not violate the Interface Segregation Principle (ISP). The interfaces are segregated well and each interface has only one responsibility.

Overall, this code follows SOLID principles with a score of 5/5 for Single Responsibility Principle (SRP), Open Closed Principle (OCP) is not violated as the class can be extended without modifying it, Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) and Interface Segregation Principle (ISP) are also followed. Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP) is partially followed because some classes depend on concrete implementations of interfaces.

